<%!-- ============================================================
  Security & compliance
============================================================ --%>

<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:security} />

  <%!-- Hero --%>
  <section class="py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-base font-semibold text-brand-400">Security &amp; compliance</p>
      <.marketing_heading tag="h1" scale={:display} class="mt-2">
        Built so your security team says yes.
      </.marketing_heading>
      <p class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        emisar exists because giving an LLM raw shell access is reckless. Every layer here
        is designed so the LLM is the least-privileged participant in the system — and
        every action is auditable.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
        <%= for chip <- ["No inbound port on hosts", "Secrets redacted before egress", "Hash-chained audit journal", "MFA + per-user runner scopes", "No raw shell, ever"] do %>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-full border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-950/60 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-zinc-300">
            <.icon name="hero-check" class="h-3.5 w-3.5 text-brand-400" />{chip}
          </span>
        <% end %>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%!-- Trust boundary --%>
  <section class="border-y border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/40 py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-brand-400">Trust boundary</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 sm:text-5xl text-balance">
          Who can do what, by design.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400 text-pretty">
          The LLM is never trusted with privileged execution. It can only request actions
          from a catalog your team has reviewed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <%!-- The canonical architecture — a request's path through emisar. The LLM
           is untrusted and outside the boundary; everything it asks crosses the
           gate (the same mark as the home hero), runs least-privilege on your
           host, and lands in a hash-chained journal. The trusted zone carries an
           emerald glow; the untrusted client stays sky/cold. --%>
      <div data-reveal class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-2xl">
        <%!-- Untrusted zone — the client, outside the boundary --%>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-sky-500/20 bg-sky-950/10 p-5">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-9 w-9 flex-none items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-sky-500/10 text-sky-300 ring-1 ring-inset ring-sky-500/25">
              <.icon name="hero-cpu-chip" class="h-5 w-5" />
            </span>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
              <span class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-sky-300">LLM client</span>
              <span class="rounded bg-sky-500/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-sky-300/90">
                untrusted
              </span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
            Claude, Cursor, or ChatGPT asks for one catalog action over MCP — with a required
            reason. It never gets a shell, and undeclared commands don't exist to it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <%!-- the boundary — the line everything the LLM asks for must cross --%>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 px-1 py-4">
          <span class="h-px flex-1 bg-gradient-to-r from-transparent via-brand-500/40 to-brand-500/60">
          </span>
          <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5 font-mono text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-lock-closed" class="h-3 w-3" /> trust boundary
          </span>
          <span class="h-px flex-1 bg-gradient-to-l from-transparent via-brand-500/40 to-brand-500/60">
          </span>
        </div>

        <%!-- Trusted zone — gate → runner → audit, lit by the brand glow --%>
        <div class="relative space-y-3">
          <div
            class="glow-emerald pointer-events-none absolute -inset-x-6 -inset-y-3"
            aria-hidden="true"
          >
          </div>

          <div class="surface-glass relative rounded-2xl border border-brand-500/30 p-5">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-3 gap-y-2">
              <.gate_mark class="h-8 w-8 flex-none text-zinc-100" />
              <span class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-brand-300">
                The gate · control plane
              </span>
              <span class="ml-auto flex flex-none items-center gap-1.5">
                <.state_chip state={:pending} label="require approval" />
                <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3 w-3 text-zinc-600" />
                <.state_chip state={:pass} label="approved" />
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
              Evaluates policy, checks scope and pack trust, routes, and writes the audit. A risky
              action waits for a human — and it never executes a shell itself.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="flex justify-center" aria-hidden="true">
            <span class="h-4 w-px bg-gradient-to-b from-brand-500/50 to-brand-500/20"></span>
          </div>

          <div class="relative rounded-2xl border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-950/70 p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
              <span class="flex h-9 w-9 flex-none items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-zinc-900 text-brand-400 ring-1 ring-inset ring-zinc-700">
                <.icon name="hero-server-stack" class="h-5 w-5" />
              </span>
              <span class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
                Runner · on your host
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
              Outbound WSS only — the host dials out, nothing listens. A non-root service user
              re-validates every argument against the schema, re-verifies the pack hash, drops to
              least privilege, runs argv arrays (never a shell string), and redacts before egress.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="flex justify-center" aria-hidden="true">
            <span class="h-4 w-px bg-gradient-to-b from-brand-500/50 to-brand-500/20"></span>
          </div>

          <div class="relative rounded-2xl border border-zinc-800 bg-zinc-950/70 p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
              <span class="flex h-9 w-9 flex-none items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-zinc-900 text-brand-400 ring-1 ring-inset ring-zinc-700">
                <.icon name="hero-document-check" class="h-5 w-5" />
              </span>
              <span class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
                Hash-chained journal + cloud audit
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="mt-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
              Every input, output, exit code, and redaction — a SHA-256-chained JSONL journal on the
              host, mirrored to the searchable cloud audit and streamable to your SIEM.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%!-- Data handling --%>
  <section class="py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-brand-400">Data handling</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 sm:text-5xl text-balance">
          Boring, defensible defaults.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mx-auto mt-16 grid max-w-5xl grid-cols-1 gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-lock-closed" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">TLS-only transport</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Runners connect to the control plane over WSS using TLS 1.2+. A bootstrap key is
            exchanged for a per-runner token that can be revoked from the dashboard.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-arrow-up-on-square" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">
            No inbound connections to runners
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Runners are outbound-only. No ports to expose, no firewall holes, no NAT traversal.
            Your hosts initiate every connection.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-document-text" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Hash-chained audit journal</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Every action is recorded to an append-only JSONL audit on the host, with each
            line carrying the SHA-256 of the previous entry. Any edited line or break in the
            chain is caught by <code class="text-zinc-300">emisar audit verify</code>; the
            cloud audit is the durable system of record.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-finger-print" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Hash-pinned packs</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Action packs are content-addressed. New, custom, or changed hashes block dispatch
            until an admin trusts the contents. Before execution, the runner recomputes the
            cloud-pinned hash and rejects a mismatch. This is content integrity, not publisher
            signing — the runner trusts the exact bytes an admin approved.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-eye-slash" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Secrets redacted before egress</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            20+ built-in patterns — AWS keys, common provider tokens (GitHub, Slack, Stripe,
            OpenAI, …), JWTs, bearer and basic auth, private-key blocks, and secret assignments —
            plus your own per-action rules scrub stdout and stderr on the runner before anything is
            forwarded. The control plane receives only the redacted stream; per-rule hit counts are
            recorded so you can see what was masked.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-brand-500/10 text-brand-400">
            <.icon name="hero-arrow-down-tray" class="h-6 w-6" />
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">
            SIEM export, least-privilege token
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            The cloud audit is the searchable system of record. Stream it to your SIEM as NDJSON
            with cursor pagination, using a dedicated read-only audit key — so your SIEM never holds
            a token that can execute an action.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%!-- Org controls --%>
  <section class="border-y border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/40 py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-brand-400">Organizational controls</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 sm:text-5xl text-balance">
          The knobs your IAM team expects.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mx-auto mt-16 grid max-w-6xl grid-cols-1 gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <.icon name="hero-user-group" class="h-7 w-7 text-brand-400" />
          <h3 class="mt-4 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-50">RBAC</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Roles for owner, admin, operator, and viewer, plus per-user runner and runner-group
            scopes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <.icon name="hero-key" class="h-7 w-7 text-brand-400" />
          <h3 class="mt-4 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-50">Scoped LLM access</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            Each MCP key is scoped — read-only, execute, or audit-only — with its own user
            attribution and runner filters. Keys are revocable and inherit their creator's runner
            scope at call time — revoke the user and every key they minted shrinks with them.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <.icon name="hero-shield-check" class="h-7 w-7 text-brand-400" />
          <h3 class="mt-4 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-50">MFA</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            TOTP (RFC 6238) on every plan, with one-time recovery codes and replay protection.
            Enforce it org-wide with one switch.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-8">
          <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
            <.icon name="hero-identification" class="h-7 w-7 text-brand-400" />
            <span class="rounded-full border border-zinc-700 px-2 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-zinc-400">
              Enterprise
            </span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="mt-4 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-50">SSO &amp; SCIM</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-400">
            OIDC sign-in with Google Workspace, Okta, or Keycloak, plus SCIM directory sync.
            Offboard someone in your IdP and their emisar sessions and keys are revoked
            automatically — <.link
              navigate={~p"/docs/sso"}
              class="text-brand-300 hover:text-brand-200"
            >see the docs</.link>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%!-- Built for assume breach — the Anthropic Zero Trust framing plus the
    host-side admission control that backs it. --%>
  <section class="py-24 sm:py-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-base font-semibold text-brand-400">Independent standard</p>
      <.marketing_heading tag="h2" scale={:section} class="mt-2">
        Built for &ldquo;assume breach.&rdquo;
      </.marketing_heading>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400 text-pretty">
        Anthropic — the lab behind Claude — published <a
          href="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/6a1611a04085d7cd3dadc924_Claude-eBook-Zero-Trust-for-AI-Agents-05182026.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-brand-300 underline decoration-zinc-700 underline-offset-4 hover:text-brand-200"
        >Zero Trust for AI Agents</a>, a framework for giving autonomous agents access to real
        systems: least agency, deny-by-default tools, human approval for high-risk actions, and an
        immutable audit trail. emisar enforces that control set — and assumes the agent may already
        be compromised, so a jailbroken or prompt-injected model still can't exceed the declared,
        gated, audited catalog.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-300">Local admission control</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
          Beyond the cloud policy, an operator can set an allow/deny list on the runner itself.
          Denied actions are hidden from the catalog and refused at execution — fail-closed, even
          against a compromised control plane. The host always has the last word.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-300">
          Signed dispatch — the cloud can't act for you
        </h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
          A runner can be set to refuse the control plane's authority entirely: it runs only an
          action a real person signed in their own MCP client, with an Ed25519 key that never
          leaves their machine. A fully compromised emisar control plane can relay that signed
          request — it can never forge, alter, replay, or originate one. The signature, not the
          cloud, is the authority. Opt-in per runner; a runner can only make itself stricter.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-x-6 gap-y-2 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/zero-trust"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-semibold text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          See emisar mapped to the framework, control by control
          <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-4 w-4" />
        </.link>
        <span class="text-xs text-zinc-500">Not affiliated with or endorsed by Anthropic.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%!-- Responsible disclosure --%>
  <section class="pb-24 sm:pb-32">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60 p-12">
        <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50">Responsible disclosure</h2>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400 text-pretty">
          Found a security issue? We want to hear about it. Email
          <a href="mailto:security@emisar.dev" class="text-brand-300 hover:text-brand-200">
            security@emisar.dev
          </a>
          with a description and reproduction steps. We acknowledge within one business day
          and credit reporters in our security advisories.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-zinc-500">
          Full policy in <a
            href="https://github.com/andrewdryga/emisar/blob/main/.github/SECURITY.md"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-brand-300 hover:text-brand-200"
          >SECURITY.md</a>.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex items-center gap-6">
          <.marketing_button
            external
            href="https://github.com/andrewdryga/emisar/blob/main/.github/SECURITY.md"
            size={:lg}
            icon="hero-arrow-top-right-on-square"
          >
            Read SECURITY.md
          </.marketing_button>
          <a
            href="mailto:security@emisar.dev"
            class="text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100 hover:text-brand-300"
          >
            Email security team <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <.marketing_cta
    headline="Ready to evaluate emisar for your team?"
    subcopy="Start free on the Free plan, or book a walkthrough and bring your security team's questions."
    secondary_label="Talk to sales"
    secondary_path="mailto:sales@emisar.dev"
  />

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
